Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Status conference on December 29, 2022 at 08:30 am.

8:20 AM Defendant Anthony James O'Claire appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek appeared by video for Anthony James O'Claire.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin in court.  Prosecuting attorney Alexander Paul Seifert in court for the State of Wisconsin. State - here for a waiver of PH and victim notification requirements have been complied with. Svehlek has e-filed the waiver of PH form. Court reviews case, filed on 10/3/22, does have form, asks if Ms. Svehlek went thru it with her client. Svehlek states she did at the time of the filing and advised him of his right to PH - makes statement as to Court only needing to find bind over on one count in the complaint. Court agrees and finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his right to PH, finds probable cause, binds over for trial. State has prepared the Information but not filed yet. Svehlek would like to set this matter for ARGN and would like to be heard on bond today. Court asks if State is willing to do that without notification for the victim. State is willing to proceed stating that the victim has not responded to any correspondence from the State and has not participated in any matters. Court will hear the motion to modify bond. Svehlek - bond - makes argument for a high signature bond. State - bond - leaves up to the discretion of the Court but does put on record the attitude/demeanor of the defendant in the past - believes some cash is warranted for stated reasons. Court - bond - sets bond at $500.00 cash and $4500.00 signature bond with same conditions. Svehlek also renews her original motion to withdraw as counsel for stated reasons. O'Claire responds. Court grants request for withdrawal and informs defendant that it will delay matters, Svehlek to file appropriate paperwork. Court sets for STC on 12/29/22 at 8:30 AM. State has filed the Information now.

10:58 AM Defendant Anthony James O'Claire not in court.  Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek appeared by video for Anthony James O'Claire.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin in court.  Attorney Charles James Simono in court for State of Wisconsin. State - here for PH but was informed that witnesses were no longer necessary as there was a request for substitution filed and was also informed that the matter would be called to address bond. Svehlek agrees, filed RFS on Friday, 10/7/22. Court advises parties that he did not see the RFS until this morning as it was filed late Friday afternoon. Court finds the RFS was filed timely and in proper form, does want to address bond and makes statements as it relates to the defendant's past appearance and demeanor in Court. Court - 969.08(2) - can consider bond adjustments - has reviewed the defendant's criminal history as was not advised of that at the time that bond originally set and finds the defendant has a significant criminal history - the filing of RFS does not excuse his presence for today - sets bond at $5,000.00 cash with no consumption of alcohol, must sign and return to Clerk of Court within 10 days - if not paid by the end of today, Court will issue a bench warrant for his arrest. State asks for conditions of no entry into any bars or taverns and no use or possession of THC or any derivatives of THC. Discussion on no contact with victim. Court will add those conditions, does grant the RFS, Ms. Svehlek's motion to withdraw would have to be filed when a new Judge is assigned if that is still her intent. Svehlek asks for bond to resemble his other bonds in other counties at this time, $3500.00 cash, would normally ask for $500.00 cash. Svehlek states that she gave the defendant permission to no appear today due to the filing of RFS and asks if that changes the Judge's mind on the new bond/possible warrant. Court did consider that, was specific that the defendant was to be here in person at the last hearing and will not take that into consideration. Svehlek will inform the defendant of the new amount of bond that is to be posted today. Adjourned.

10:57 AM Defendant Anthony James O'Claire appeared by video with leave of the Court as the PH is being waived today.  Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek appeared by video for Anthony James O'Claire.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin in court.  Prosecuting attorney Alexander Paul Seifert in court for the State of Wisconsin. State - here for PH and believe it is being waived. O'Claire states that he does not want to waive his PH now. Svehlek asks for a breakout room to talk to her client. Court will not allow a breakout room and will set matte for a PH ASAP. Svehlek asks to withdraw from case stating that she no longer wishes to represent the defendant. Defendant agrees stating he does not want to continue this case with Attorney Svehlek. Court will not allow the withdrawal of Ms. Svehlek, tells clerk to set matter for a PH. O'Claire raises voice stating he does not want Atty Svehlek on his case, continues to talk over both Atty Svehlek and the Court. Court sets for PH on 10/10/22 at 11:00 AM, parties to appear in person. Defendant continues to make belligerent comments. Court adjourns today's proceeding and removes defendant from the hearing.

9:49 AM Defendant Anthony James O'Claire not in court.  Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek appeared by video for Anthony James O'Claire.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin in court.  Prosecuting attorney Alexander Paul Seifert in court for the State of Wisconsin. Court puts on the record what transpired with the defendant this morning, wanted to appear via Zoom, states he was not going to drive 5 hours to be here today, was informed several times that he had to appear in person. State asks for bench warrant, body or $1000.00. Svehlek states that her client does not have transportation to appear in person, asks Court to excuse his appearance for today, asks for a PH in which she will inform the defendant will need to be here in person. Court will issue the bench warrant, body or $2000.00, once arrested or posted - can set for PH then. Svehlek asks for a lower warrant amount of $250.00. Court keeping warrant at $2000.00 cash for stated reasons, defendant's demeanor in the past for court appearances and with the Clerk's staff. Svehlek makes statements as it relates to his demeanor, states she is able to control the defendant after long talks. Court responds. State responds, leaves decision up to the Court. Court will not issue a bench warrant, sets for PH on 9/12/22 at 11:00 AM.
